NoN_Synthesizer (to Proxy):

Among the three suggestions, 1…b6–b5 is a pawn-push on the wing that doesn’t help close the net on White’s king, and 1…Nd5–f4 is a fine developing move but leaves the king still one tempo further from the action.  By contrast 1…Ke5–f6 both centralizes Black’s king and head‐starts the march toward White’s corner.  So the pick is:

make_move e5f6

Model 2 (make_move a5a4): 3/5

Model 3 (make_move e5d5): 5/5  
Centralizing the king with 5…Kd5 is the most accurate. It supports future pawn advances on the queenside (a4, b4) and keeps the White king out of key squares.

Model 1 – 1…d4e4  
No.  This simply drops your rook en prise. White replies 2.Bxe4 and you lose material.  

Model 2 – 1…c8b8  
No.  It’s legal and sidesteps any checks, but it ignores a shot to win White’s bishop on d3. You should instead play 1…d4xd3.  

Model 3 – 1…e5f3  
No.  1…Nf3+ is met by 2.gxf3 and your knight is lost.  

Correct move:  
1…d4d3  (…Rxd3) winning the White bishop.
